The '''Avogadro constant''', commonly denoted {{mvar|'''N{{sub|{{ni|A}}}}'''}}<ref name=bipm9th/> or {{mvar|'''L'''}},<ref name=iupac1996/> is the [[proportionality factor]] that relates the [[particle number|number of constituent particle]]s (usually [[molecule]]s, [[atom]]s or [[ion]]s) in a sample with the [[amount of substance]] in that sample. It is an [[International System of Units|SI defining constant]] with an exact value of {{val|6.02214076|e=23|u=[[mole (unit)|reciprocal moles]]}}.<ref name="SI2019"/><ref name=ciaaw/> It is named after the Italian scientist [[Amedeo Avogadro]]<ref name=perrin1909/> by [[Stanislao Cannizzaro]], who explained this number four years after Avogadro's death while at the [[Karlsruhe Congress]] in 1860.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Stanislao Cannizzaro {{!}} Science History Institute |url=https://www.sciencehistory.org/historical-profile/stanislao-cannizzaro |access-date=June 2, 2022 |website=Science History Institute|date=June 2016 }}</ref>

The numeric value of the Avogadro constant expressed in reciprocal moles, a dimensionless number, is called the '''Avogadro number'''. In older literature, the Avogadro number is denoted {{mvar|N}}<ref name=pauling/><ref name=mcgraw/> or {{mvar|N{{sub|{{ni|0}}}}}},<ref name=feynman/><ref name=born/> which is the number of particles that are contained in one mole, exactly {{val|6.02214076|e=23|u=}}.<ref name="SI2019"/>

The value of the Avogadro constant was chosen so that the mass of one mole of a [[chemical compound]], in [[gram]]s, is numerically equal (for all practical purposes) to the average mass of one molecule of the compound in [[Dalton (unit)|daltons (universal atomic mass units)]]; one dalton being {{sfrac|1|12}} of the mass of one [[carbon-12]] atom, which is approximately the mass of one [[nucleon]] ([[proton]] or [[neutron]]). For example, the average mass of one molecule of [[water]] is about 18.0153&nbsp;daltons, and one mole of water ({{mvar|N}} molecules) is about 18.0153&nbsp;grams. Thus, the Avogadro constant {{mvar|N{{sub|{{ni|A}}}}}} is the [[proportionality factor]] that relates the [[molar mass]] of a substance to the average [[mass]] of one molecule, and the Avogadro number is also the approximate number of nucleons in one gram of ordinary [[matter]].<ref name=okun/>

The Avogadro constant also relates the [[molar volume]] of a substance to the average volume nominally occupied by one of its particles, when both are expressed in the same units of volume. For example, since the molar volume of water in ordinary conditions is about 18&nbsp;mL/[[millilitre|mol]], the volume occupied by one molecule of water is about {{nowrap|{{sfrac|18|6.022}}{{e|-23}} mL}}, or about {{val|30|u=√Ö3}} (cubic [[angstrom]]s). For a [[crystal]]line substance, it similarly relates its molar volume (in mol/mL), the volume of the repeating [[crystal structure|unit cell]] of the crystals (in mL), and the number of molecules in that cell.

The Avogadro number (or constant) has been defined in many different ways through its long history. Its approximate value was first determined, indirectly, by [[Johann Josef Loschmidt|Josef Loschmidt]] in 1865.<ref name="losch1865"/> (Avogadro's number is closely related to the [[Loschmidt constant]], and the two concepts are sometimes confused.) It was initially defined by [[Jean Baptiste Perrin|Jean Perrin]] as the number of atoms in 16&nbsp;grams of [[oxygen]].<ref name=perrin1909/> It was later redefined in the 14th conference of the [[International Bureau of Weights and Measures]] (BIPM) as the number of atoms in 12&nbsp;grams of the isotope [[carbon-12]] (<sup>12</sup>C).<ref name=bipm8th/> In each case, the mole was defined as the quantity of a substance that contained the same number of atoms as those reference samples. In particular, when carbon-12 was the reference, one mole of carbon-12 was exactly 12&nbsp;grams of the element.

These definitions meant that the value of the Avogadro number depended on the experimentally determined value of the mass (in grams) of one atom of those elements, and therefore it was known only to a limited number of decimal digits. However, in its 26th Conference, the BIPM adopted a different approach: effective 20 May 2019, it defined the Avogadro number {{mvar|N}} as the exact value {{physconst|NA|unit=no|ref=no}}, and redefined the mole as the amount of a substance under consideration that contains {{mvar|N}} constituent particles of the substance. Under the new definition, the mass of one mole of any substance (including hydrogen, carbon-12, and oxygen-16) is {{mvar|N}} times the average mass of one of its constituent particles &ndash; a physical quantity whose precise value has to be determined experimentally for each substance.

==History==

===Origin of the concept===
[[File:Jean Perrin 1926.jpg|right|thumb|Jean Perrin in 1926]]
The Avogadro constant is named after the Italian scientist [[Amedeo Avogadro]] (1776‚Äì1856), who, in 1811, first proposed that the volume of a gas (at a given pressure and temperature) is proportional to the number of [[atom]]s or [[molecule]]s regardless of the nature of the gas.<ref name=avog1811/>

The name ''Avogadro's number'' was coined in 1909 by the physicist [[Jean Baptiste Perrin|Jean Perrin]], who defined it as the number of molecules in exactly 16 grams of [[oxygen]].<ref name=perrin1909/> The goal of this definition was to make the mass of a mole of a substance, in grams, be numerically equal to the mass of one molecule relative to the mass of the hydrogen atom; which, because of the [[law of definite proportions]], was the natural unit of atomic mass, and was assumed to be 1/16 of the atomic mass of oxygen.

===First measurements===
[[File:Johann Josef Loschmidt portrait plaque.jpg|right|thumb|Josef Loschmidt]]
The value of Avogadro's number (not yet known by that name) was first obtained indirectly by [[Johann Josef Loschmidt|Josef Loschmidt]] in 1865, by estimating the number of particles in a given volume of gas.<ref name=losch1865/> This value, the [[number density]] {{mvar|n{{sub|{{ni|0}}}}}} of particles in an [[ideal gas]], is now called the [[Loschmidt constant]] in his honor, and is related to the Avogadro constant, {{mvar|N{{sub|{{ni|A}}}}}}, by
:<math>n_0 = \frac{p_0N_{\rm A}}{R\,T_0}</math>,
where {{mvar|p{{sub|{{ni|0}}}}}} is the [[pressure]], {{mvar|R}} is the [[gas constant]], and {{mvar|T{{sub|{{ni|0}}}}}} is the [[absolute temperature]]. Because of this work, the symbol {{mvar|L}} is sometimes used for the Avogadro constant,<ref name=bipm1971/> and, in [[German language|German]] literature, that name may be used for both constants, distinguished only by the [[units of measurement]].<ref name=virgo1933/> (However, {{mvar|N{{sub|{{ni|A}}}}}} should not be confused with the entirely different [[Loschmidt constant]] in English-language literature.)

Perrin himself determined Avogadro's number by several different experimental methods. He was awarded the 1926 [[Nobel Prize in Physics]], largely for this work.<ref name=oseen1926/>

The electric charge per [[Mole (unit)|mole]] of electrons is a constant called the [[Faraday constant]] and has been known since 1834, when [[Michael Faraday]] published [[Faraday's laws of electrolysis|his works on electrolysis]]. In 1910, [[Robert Millikan]] obtained the first measurement of the [[elementary charge|charge on an electron]]. Dividing the charge on a mole of electrons by the charge on a single electron provided a more accurate estimate of the Avogadro number.<ref name=ebrit1974/>

===SI definition of 1971===
In 1971, the International Bureau of Weights and Measures (BIPM) decided to regard the [[amount of substance]] as an independent [[dimensional analysis|dimension of measurement]], with the mole as its [[SI unit|base unit]] in the [[International System of Units]] (SI).<ref name=bipm1971/> Specifically, the mole was defined as an amount of a substance that contains as many elementary entities as there are atoms in {{nowrap|0.012 kilograms of [[carbon-12]]}}.

By this definition, the common rule of thumb that "one gram of matter contains {{mvar|N{{sub|{{ni|0}}}}}} nucleons" was exact for carbon-12, but slightly inexact for other elements and isotopes. On the other hand, one mole of any substance contained exactly as many molecules as one mole of any other substance.

As a consequence of this definition, in the SI system the Avogadro constant {{mvar|N{{sub|{{ni|A}}}}}} had the [[dimensional analysis|dimensionality]] of reciprocal of amount of substance rather than of a pure number, and had the approximate value {{val|6.02|e=23}} with units of mol{{sup|‚àí1}}.<ref name=bipm1971/> By this definition, the value of {{mvar|N{{sub|{{ni|A}}}}}} inherently had to be determined experimentally.

The BIPM also named {{mvar|N{{sub|{{ni|A}}}}}} the "Avogadro ''constant''", but the term "Avogadro number" continued to be used especially in introductory works.<ref name=kotz2008/>

===SI redefinition of 2019===
{{main|2019 redefinition of the SI base units}}
In 2017, the BIPM decided to change the definitions of mole and amount of substance.<ref name=cipm106/><ref name="SI2019"/> The mole was redefined as being the amount of substance containing exactly {{val|6.02214076|e=23}} elementary entities. One consequence of this change is that the mass of a mole of <sup>12</sup>C atoms is no longer exactly 0.012&nbsp;kg. On the other hand, the dalton ({{aka}} universal atomic mass unit) remains unchanged as {{sfrac|1|12}} of the mass of <sup>12</sup>C.<ref name=pave2018/><ref name=IUPAC/> Thus, the [[molar mass constant]] is no longer exactly 1&nbsp;g/mol, although the difference ({{val|4.5|e=-10}} in relative terms, as of March 2019) is insignificant for practical purposes.<ref name="SI2019"/><ref name=bipm9th/>

==Connection to other constants==

The Avogadro constant {{mvar|N{{sub|{{ni|A}}}}}} is related to other physical constants and properties.

* It relates the [[molar gas constant]] {{mvar|R}} and the [[Boltzmann constant]] {{mvar|k{{sub|{{ni|B}}}}}}, which in the SI is defined to be exactly {{val|1.380649|e=‚àí23|u=J/K}}:<ref name="SI2019"/>
